metadata.name: Breakdown #180
metadata.description:
The key to solving a difficult problem is to break it down into a series of smaller, more tractable, problems.

Here we start with a rectangular polygon. We shrink our polygon by some fixed amount (inset), and then pick a point inside it. We then send off rays in N evenly spaced directions and use these to split the polygon into N new polygons. Repeat the process, varying parameters such as how we pick our point or the angles of our projected rays, and see what emerges.

Press 'v' to download an svg output.

metadata.name: Dark Stars #1
metadata.description:
In astronomy, black holes are incredibly dense regions of space where the gravitational force is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from it. A black hole is literally a tear in the fabric of spacetime. Such a thing can only be created by the collapse of a massive starâ€“or possibly by a dark star. 

In philosophical terms, a black hole is a place where everything is pulled into a single point. It is the end of all things; the mind becomes totalitarian, and the self is lost.

Dark stars and black holes may represent an endingâ€“a finalityâ€“but generative art is a beginning. Generative projects have the potential to change the way we think about art and life.

Art can be one way that our consciousness avoids falling into a black hole. By appreciating the beauty in nature, we can find hope and avoid becoming trapped in an endless abyss. 

So it is with generative art; from the darkness of a black hole, from the mystery of a dark star, new ideas and new ways of seeing the world are born.

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save the image.

metadata.name: CMYK:Split #59
metadata.description:
CMYK:Split uses code to blow apart the CMYK screens used to produce the printed portraits, then scale and position randomly on the X axis.

The four individual female portraits within this piece have been generated using AI.

Please Note: Once your hash-generated composition has been shown the piece will continue to create further infinite compositions.

metadata.name: strokes-1 #9
metadata.description:
A generative abstract painting using layers of strokes of different size, strength and color.

The painting is rendered by simulating one stroke at a time. The recipe is similar for all paintings. First, wide faint brush strokes cover the canvas with a background texture, then a few strong brush strokes give the piece some character. After that, very fine rapid strokes give the piece some interesting detail and finally, dabs of very short brush strokes are applied for additional sense of depth. 

The rendering takes some time. With large screen sizes, you get bigger pictures (for printing!), but the rendering is slower. 

Once the work is painted, you can hit 's' to save a png file. 

There are 7 different colour schemes.
